                    </div>
<p>The 2025 Z900 continues to reflect Kawasaki’s<span class="font-weight-700"> Sugomi design language, </span>emphasizing a crouched stance and predator-like aesthetics.</p>
<p><span class="font-weight-700"> Styling Highlights: </span> </p>
<ul>
	<li>A more angular headlight housing with <span class="font-weight-700"> refined LED DRLs </span></li>
	<li>Reshaped tank extensions for a more muscular profile</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700"> New color themes </span> including Metallic Matte Graphene Steel Gray and Ebony Lime Green</li>
	<li>Updated <span class="font-weight-700"> underbelly cowl </span>and rear tail tidy for a sleeker finish</li>
</ul>
<p>The bike still oozes aggression but now wears its attitude with a slightly more polished edge.</p>
<div class="div-line"></div>
<h3 class="subheading">Engine and Performance</h3>
                <div class="row m-b20">
                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12 text-center image-height"><img src="~/images/blogs/2025/june/KawasakiZ900/leftside.webp" alt="bikecarhubleftside" title="bikecarhubleftside" /></div>
                </div>
<p>At its heart, the 2025 Z900 retains the iconic <span class="font-weight-700"> 948cc inline-four engine, </span>known for its linear power delivery and thrilling exhaust note.</p>
<ul>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Power: </span>124 PS@9500 rpm</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Torque:</span> 97.4 Nm@7700 rpm</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Transmission:</span> 6-speed with assist & slipper clutch</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Top Speed:</span> 230 km/h (estimated)</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">0–100 km/h: </span>3.5 seconds</li>
</ul>
<p>No drastic changes have been made mechanically, but minor tweaks to ECU mapping and emissions calibration help the bike meet updated norms like <span class="font-weight-700">BS6.2 (India) </span>or<span class="font-weight-700"> Euro 5+ (Global).</span>
<div class="div-line"></div>

<h3 class="subheading">Chassis, Suspension & Braking</h3>
                    <div class="row m-b20">
                        <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12 text-center image-height"><img src="~/images/blogs/2025/june/KawasakiZ900/frontred.webp" alt="bikecarhubfrontred" title="bikecarhubleftfrontred" /></div>
                    </div>
                <p>Kawasaki continues with its proven <span class="font-weight-700">high-tensile steel trellis frame, </span>ensuring a balance between rigidity and rider feedback.</p>
<p><span class="font-weight-700">Hardware Includes:</span></p>
<ul>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">41mm USD front forks</span> (adjustable for rebound and preload)</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Horizontal back-link rear mono-shock</span> (also adjustable)</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Brakes: </span>Dual 300mm front discs with 4-piston calipers, 250mm rear disc</li>
	<li><span class="font-weight-700">Tyres: </span>120/70 front and 180/55 rear (17-inch alloys)</li>
</ul>
<p>This setup gives the Z900 nimble handling in city traffic and solid stability at highway speeds.</p>
<div class="div-line"></div>

<h3 class="subheading">Electronics & Rider Aids</h3>
